{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/preprocessing-customisation-over-the-usual-drill-3ce49c583779", "time": 1683017396.100186, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/preprocessing-customisation-over-the-usual-drill-3ce49c583779/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Preprocessing: Customisation over the usual drill | by Eram Munawwar | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Preprocessing: Customisation over the usual drill", "description": "It is often said that data scientists spend almost 70% of their time in feature engineering. With NLP, the same is true for cleaning the text. Almost all real life NLP datasets are extremely\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://pypi.org/project/Sastrawi/", "anchor_text": "Sastrawi Stemmer", "paragraph_index": 3}], "all_paragraphs": ["It is often said that data scientists spend almost 70% of their time in feature engineering. With NLP, the same is true for cleaning the text. Almost all real life NLP datasets are extremely unstructured. Sources like social media, customer reviews, even news articles or wikipedia data are exploding with information, all of which might not be needed for our use case. They all need to be processed for feature extraction.", "When it comes to text preprocessing, there is a tendency to follow a usual drill. I will be talking more about the drill in the coming section. On a high level, it is a 5\u20136 step standard preprocessing which includes lowercasing, removing stop words, numbers, punctuations and stemming or lemmatising the data. And then finally tokenise the text to words. You\u2019ll see a ton of blogs and articles revolving around this drill.", "However, working with specific NLP problems like Question Answering, Named Entity extraction, topic modelling etc., I have learnt that giving more time to customised preprocessing can give a pretty good boost to the model\u2019s overall performance. Moreover, the drill usually fails when working with any language other than english. Working with Bahasa Indonesia on a daily basis, I realised that customisation is key to preprocessing.", "Stemming and lemmatisation might not be very beneficial when working with the english language. However, if we\u2019re working with another language, e.g. Bahasa Indonesia, each word comes with almost 5\u20136 variants by adding prefixes and suffixes to it. Therefore stemming becomes very essential. Or else the vocabulary size would be too high! For the Indonesian language, Sastrawi Stemmer is the best one I have encountered so far. Do check it out if you\u2019re also working with Bahasa!", "Now that we understand what the preprocessing drill looks like, along with the dangers of following it blindly, let us see a rule of thumb for custom preprocessing.", "Below are tricks that I use for picking up the best preprocessing for my use case.", "Some more steps in preprocessing can be:", "Text preprocessing can be tedious but its advantages cannot be denied. Instead of doing it all, we must try to follow the rule of thumb to get a pretty clean and usable text, ready for feature extraction.", "Many times, I have used pre-trained models on a custom dataset for transfer learning and seen that a few additional customisations in preprocessing has yielded a higher score than without it.", "I hope the general knowledge about text cleaning and my tricks of customisation would be helpful for your NLP tasks. Let\u2019s keep in mind that sometimes less can be enough! It is not required to do all the steps, instead, a few might be better.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "An NLP and Deep Learning enthusiast who has been in this field for over 6 years. My focus areas lie in MRC, NLG and NLU. Concepts over Jargon!"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F3ce49c583779&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav-------------------